Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria led to a marked weakening of the two parties forming the present great coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly serious losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Governor of Carinthie Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphal return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 per cent of the votes, the country's first political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 per cent of the votes.
The ÖVP, which lost nearly nine percent of the votes at 25.6 percent, ended up even worse.
These are the worst results of the two great parties in the post-war period; especially for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
However, voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer was pronounced.
The observers believe that this could happen on Monday, during the extraordinary leadership council of the party.
Such an evolution would, a priori, facilitate the way to the outcome of the election, which remains the most likely outcome, namely the renewal of the major SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Nevertheless, in view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 per cent and BZÖ 11 per cent of the votes - the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition in 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated from it) on a common government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he is planning to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently based on this development.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four per cent limit and did not enter parliament.
