If the problem of the Czech researchers accused in India of illegally picking cockroaches could not be resolved, the Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg said that this would lead to a certain cooling of the Czech-Indian relations.
The Minister declared it today in New York, after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not resolved, then yes, a certain cooling would occur," he observed after the meeting, carried out following a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, after the talks, that it was difficult for the executive to intervene in judicial matters.
He mentioned, however, that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was discharged from charge and fined, the central government could negotiate with the local government, the Darjeling government, and the case was under its jurisdiction.
