A Czech arbiter the struggle for the bottom of the sea
It is nearing an electronic mural map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are represented.
However, he was not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"It belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
However, this area is as large as the continent itself, "said Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the United Nations Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the head of the division, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The prevailing atmosphere is characterized by hard work and enthusiasm.
The seafloor hides a world that has so far been little known, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found there, but also living organisms for the time being unknown, which may contain the key to the development of a cancer medicine.
A larger bottom than the land
The littoral states have now begun to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they use their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometres from the coast of the given country.
According to the Convention, the latter may claim exclusively all the resources of the continental shelf.
"For simplicity, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered a continental shelf.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the 200 nautical miles that represent said exclusive economic yone, "Mikulka explains.
The request made by the country in question to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by a wide range of scientific and technical documentation based on many expensive prospections and metrics.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the Commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
To date, the Commission has dealt with five applications, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
For the time being, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful, "Mikulka adds.
Australia's success, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater possessions, has recently had a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which was allocated to it by the commission last week, is 1.6 million square kilometres, which is the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospections.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they plan to do, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They may do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention."
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean bottom, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of mankind."
There, no single state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area shall be assigned by an international institution established by convention.
"However, let us not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, exaggerating that "its areas are clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the joint organisation "Interoceanmetal."
In 1991, under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other states, it obtained the status of the so-called "pioneer investor."
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaii Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is eventful, it is a sort of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract over an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometres.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese, "says Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
