Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey thought about joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to enter its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps away, from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of its fallen imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is placed on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, with observation towers at each corner, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticketing, we have no doubt more about the size of the company, which represents a westward passage.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retarded imperialist, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination thanks to this railroad that arrives in Damascus, Baghdad as well as the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregularities.
The relative isolation of its surrounding area, generated by the cold war's frozen borders, is over.
The British and empire forces advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources claim that this is a sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into ruins, swallowed up in the meanders of history.
But today, the rail passage to Anatolia and all the oriental points, serve - at least symbolically - to emphasize the enlargement of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new commitment policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on a sleeper car in the direction of the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit the Turkish MP AKP Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a journey of 10 hours and a half, shaken on noisy tracks whose pace reminded the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived, in the Turkish capital - presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning my back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots is an example of a change in the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, specifically built in stone and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and numerous pastries in which middle managers in suit-suits - men and women - meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Suit, tie, and he even has a Black Berry.
"the aim of this foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly, "he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for both.
She had to do both.
"but, now, at some point," I asked if "Turkey should not choose?"
"Turkey," he said, "does not want to have to choose between the two."
He then pointed out an aspect that almost everyone with whom I have been able to speak has recited to me by heart: the Turkish railway is not only going to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as it is for Turkey itself.
With the integration of Turkey, the message seems to draw a Europe that is metaphorically travelling on the rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the station in Hydarpasha, after another night without sleeping, I thought of the two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
While I was waiting at the terminal, the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the period during which Turkey had been named "the sick of Europe."
At least there is no more doubt on the continent that could claim this fascinating country.
