Mark Brown writes: Music director at Guildford since 1962, Vermon "Tod" Handley (died September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Already part of his musical project for the city, he founded the fantastic youth choir Proteus the following year.
The choir was supposed to include the under-21, but before Proteus could sing his last song in 1979, many of us who were over 20 years old refused to abandon the choir.
The name "Proteus" (which changed form according to mythology) represented the will and ability of the choir to manage any type of music, whether madrigal or Messianic.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often impressive, always exciting, thanks to the inspiration of one man, and his enthusiasm for music, which remained constant over the years.
Remember how Tod kept telling us to "let the music speak for itself."
He would have said, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all there, in the music.
So sing! "
His wand technique was absolutely clear, precise, even if never dictatorial or appearing.
Whatever the music standard, he raised it a lot higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a driver is to be named a knight, it's Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the decades from 1962 to 1982, when he was driving the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years, I've seen more than a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that none of them ever let me down - and sometimes they even inspired me.
