The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has, this time, been inspired by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating bee theft, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Centre made this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow the brand vehicles to prevent collisions.
During his flight, each bee creates his own personal space of an oval shape that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the eyes composed of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is known as a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles over a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"As soon as it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by twisting its wheels of 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, "explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Travel Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down, nor diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
"Each second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logic of prior manoeuvres, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB memory.
This may be surprising, but we are not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes. "
This is the first car to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced in serial cars in about ten years after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
