Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Reconstitute the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like its counterparts and friends, it was the third that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls at the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization announced a large victory of the "yes" between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed victory over his draft constitution on Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held in a calm manner according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observer mission, was on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and currencies sent by its emigrants.
Carried out by Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive terms of four years and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further strengthens the principle of free health and education services, which the President has begun to establish in the country of 13.9 million people, where 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were returned this Monday afternoon safely to the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at about 3.30 p.m. on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health," and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, "said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September in a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the outskirts of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been robbed from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official reported that 30 Special Forces personnel, carried on board two helicopters, attacked in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of fire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official who requested anonymity.
He reported that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the flash unit had been sent to the Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian diplomat Franco Frattini mentioned the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces from Belgrade, where he is located.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were present, killing in six, including the Chadian chief, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately denied by the movement.
