Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries are supporting this financial and insurance institution with interest in Hungary for a sum of €11.2 billion.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also calling on the European Central Bank and the competition authority of the European Commission.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been growing for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, among which, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, the Fortis shares started a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed in the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's shares dropped by 12 percent, reaching its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's managers, is unrealistic.
The management of the company is blaming the Atlantic for the uncertainty surrounding the adoption of the US $700 billion rescue plan to be responsible for the fall of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, there has already been a slight increase in the number of papers.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new general manager.
The financial agency was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a substantive proposal.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the hen house
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of information concerning the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, with the agreement of the data subject.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting a fox to his hatchery "- said Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital depend on the health of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even guarantee it.
In the past, they sent the candidates to a medical examination, and they did not sign an insurance contract with them until they became aware of the results.
For the past ten years Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he readily obtains from pharmacies the data concerning the person's purchases of medicines within the last eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers and what his state of health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to extremely high blood fat, which puts him or her in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do for the insurer except the paperwork. However, tiny problems can still arise.
The disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flushes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data, and they must ask the patient for authorisation before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their shortcomings in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory test results, linking them with drug use data, so they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time the control of use is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the extension of the control circle of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the supply of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus, and ultimately, hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, which will focus on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and head of diplomacy Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of more than 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be too ambitious a target.
To this end, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civilian flights, and in this way air trade can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's leading trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan had been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and mention had been made of the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on that subject.
The completion of the Doha trade round was also called for, although both had a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its toxic releases by at least 20% until 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as on the need for a global market at next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is today visiting the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to information from the news agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
