Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying on the Nevada Desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 metres, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, removed the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it was the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore stated that no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The United States Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete the round of the world on an aerostatic balloon in 2002: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world without stopping.
Among all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
